[4mNVIM[24m(1)                                                                         General Commands Manual                                                                        [4mNVIM[24m(1)

[1mNAME[0m
       nvim ‚Äî edit text

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [1mnvim [22m[[4moptions[24m] [[4mfile[24m [4m...[24m]
       [1mnvim [22m[[4moptions[24m] [1m-[0m
       [1mnvim [22m[[4moptions[24m] [1m-t [4m[22mtag[0m
       [1mnvim [22m[[4moptions[24m] [1m-q [22m[[4merrorfile[24m]

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [1mnvim [22mis a text editor based on Vim.  Start [1mnvim [22mfollowed by any number of options and/or files:

             [1mnvim [options] [file ...][0m

       Commands in [1mnvim [22mbegin with colon (‚Äò:‚Äô).  Type ‚Äú:help subject‚Äù to get help on a specific subject.  Use <Tab> and CTRL-D to complete subjects (‚Äú:help cmdline-completion‚Äù).

       The ‚Äúquickref‚Äù help section is a condensed reference of editor features:
             [1m:help quickref[0m

       If you are new to Vim/Nvim, start with the 30-minute tutorial:
             [1m:Tutor[0m

       After installing/updating Nvim, it's a good idea to run the self-check:
             [1m:checkhealth[0m

       [4mfile[24m [4m...[24m    File(s) to edit.  Opens one buffer per file.  To switch between buffers, use the [1m:next [22mand [1m:previous [22mcommands.

       [1m-           [22mReads text from standard input until EOF, then opens a buffer with that text.  User input is read from standard error, which should be a terminal.

[1mOPTIONS[0m
       [1m-t [4m[22mtag[24m      Finds  [4mtag[24m  in the tags file, the associated file becomes the current file and the associated command is executed.  Cursor is positioned at the tag location in the
                   file.  [1m:help tag-commands[0m

       [1m-q [22m[[4merrorfile[24m]
                   QuickFix mode.  Display the first error in [4merrorfile[24m.  If [4merrorfile[24m is omitted, the value of the 'errorfile' option is used (defaults to [1merrors.err[22m).  Further  er‚Äê
                   rors can be jumped to with the [1m:cnext [22mcommand.  [1m:help quickfix[0m

       [1m--          [22mEnd of options.  Remaining arguments are treated as literal file names, including filenames starting with hyphen (‚Äò-‚Äô).

       [1m-e          [22mEx mode, reading stdin as Ex commands.  [1m:help Ex-mode[0m

       [1m-E          [22mEx mode, reading stdin as text.  [1m:help Ex-mode[0m

       [1m-es         [22mSilent (non-interactive) Ex mode, reading stdin as Ex commands.  Useful for scripting because it does NOT start a UI, unlike [1m-e[22m.  [1m:help silent-mode[0m

       [1m-Es         [22mSilent (non-interactive) Ex mode, reading stdin as text.  Useful for scripting because it does NOT start a UI, unlike [1m-E[22m.  [1m:help silent-mode[0m

       [1m-d          [22mDiff mode.  Show the difference between two to eight files, similar to [4msdiff[24m(1).  [1m:help diff[0m

       [1m-R          [22mRead-only  mode.  Sets the 'readonly' option.  Implies [1m-n[22m.  Buffers can still be edited, but cannot be written to disk if already associated with a file.  To over‚Äê
                   write a file, add an exclamation mark to the relevant Ex command, such as [1m:w![22m.  [1m:help 'readonly'[0m

       [1m-m          [22mResets the 'write' option, to disable file modifications.  Writing to a file is disabled, but buffers can still be modified.

       [1m-M          [22mResets the 'write' and 'modifiable' options, to disable file and buffer modifications.

       [1m-b          [22mBinary mode.  [1m:help edit-binary[0m

       [1m-A          [22mArabic mode.  Sets the 'arabic' option.

       [1m-H          [22mHebrew mode.  Sets the 'hkmap' and 'rightleft' options.

       [1m-V[22m[[4mN[24m][[4mfile[24m]
                   Verbose mode.  Prints debug messages.  [4mN[24m is the 'verbose' level, defaults to [1m10[22m.  If [4mfile[24m is specified, append messages to [4mfile[24m instead of  printing  them.   [1m:help[0m
                   [1m'verbose'[0m

       [1m-D          [22mVimscript debug mode.  Started when executing the first command from a script.  [1m:help debug-mode[0m

       [1m-n          [22mDisable the use of swap files.  Sets the 'updatecount' option to [1m0[22m.  Can be useful for editing files on a slow medium.

       [1m-r [22m[[4mfile[24m]   Recovery  mode.   If  [4mfile[24m is omitted then list swap files with recovery information.  Otherwise the swap file [4mfile[24m is used to recover a crashed session.  The swap
                   file has the same name as the file it's associated with, but with ‚Äò.swp‚Äô appended.  [1m:help recovery[0m

       [1m-L [22m[[4mfile[24m]   Alias for [1m-r[22m.

       [1m-u [4m[22mvimrc[24m    Use [4mvimrc[24m instead of the default [4m~/.config/nvim/init.vim[24m.  If [4mvimrc[24m is [1mNORC[22m, do not load any initialization files (except plugins).  If [4mvimrc[24m is [1mNONE[22m, loading plu‚Äê
                   gins is also skipped.  [1m:help initialization[0m

       [1m-i [4m[22mshada[24m    Use [4mshada[24m instead of the default [4m~/.local/state/nvim/shada/main.shada[24m.  If [4mshada[24m is [1mNONE[22m, do not read or write a ShaDa file.  [1m:help shada[0m

       [1m--noplugin  [22mSkip loading plugins (by setting the 'noloadplugins' option).  Implied by [1m-u NONE[22m.

       [1m--clean     [22mStart Nvim with ‚Äúfactory defaults‚Äù (no user config and plugins, no shada).  [1m:help --clean[0m

       [1m-o[22m[[4mN[24m]       Open [4mN[24m windows stacked horizontally.  If [4mN[24m is omitted, open one window for each file.  If [4mN[24m is less than the number of file arguments,  allocate  windows  for  the
                   first [4mN[24m files and hide the rest.

       [1m-O[22m[[4mN[24m]       Like [1m-o[22m, but tile windows vertically.

       [1m-p[22m[[4mN[24m]       Like [1m-o[22m, but for tab pages.

       [1m+[22m[[4mlinenum[24m]  For the first file, position the cursor on line [4mlinenum[24m.  If [4mlinenum[24m is omitted, position the cursor on the last line of the file.  [1m+5 [22mand [1m-c 5 [22mon the command-line
                   are equivalent to [1m:5 [22minside [1mnvim[22m.

       [1m+/[22m[[4mpattern[24m]
                   For  the first file, position the cursor on the first occurrence of [4mpattern[24m.  If [4mpattern[24m is omitted, the most recent search pattern is used (if any).  [1m+/foo [22mand [1m-c[0m
                   [1m/foo [22mon the command-line are equivalent to [1m/foo [22mand [1m:/foo [22minside [1mnvim[22m.  [1m:help search-pattern[0m

       [1m+[4m[22mcommand[24m, [1m-c [4m[22mcommand[0m
                   Execute [4mcommand[24m after reading the first file.  Up to 10 instances allowed.  "[1m+foo[22m" and [1m-c "foo" [22mare equivalent.

       [1m--cmd [4m[22mcommand[0m
                   Like [1m-c[22m, but execute [4mcommand[24m before processing any vimrc.  Up to 10 instances of these can be used independently from instances of [1m-c[22m.

       [1m-l [4m[22mscript[24m [[4margs[24m]
                   Execute Lua [4mscript[24m with optional [[4margs[24m] after processing any preceding Nvim startup arguments.  All [[4margs[24m] are treated as script arguments and are passed literally
                   to Lua, that is, [1m-l [22mstops processing of Nvim arguments.  [1m:help -l[0m

       [1m-S [22m[[4msession[24m]
                   Execute [4msession[24m after the first file argument has been read.  If [4msession[24m filename ends with [4m.lua[24m it is executed as Lua instead  of  Vimscript.   Equivalent  to  [1m-c[0m
                   [1m"source session"[22m.  [4msession[24m cannot start with a hyphen (‚Äò-‚Äô).  If [4msession[24m is omitted then [4mSession.vim[24m is used, if found.  [1m:help session-file[0m

       [1m-s [4m[22mscriptin[0m
                   Read  normal  mode  commands from [4mscriptin[24m.  The same can be done with the command [1m:source! scriptin[22m.  If the end of the file is reached before [1mnvim [22mexits, further
                   characters are read from the keyboard.

       [1m-w [4m[22mscriptout[0m
                   Append all typed characters to [4mscriptout[24m.  Can be used for creating a script to be used with [1m-s [22mor [1m:source![22m.

       [1m-W [4m[22mscriptout[0m
                   Like [1m-w[22m, but truncate [4mscriptout[24m.

       [1m--startuptime [4m[22mfile[0m
                   During startup, append timing messages to [4mfile[24m.  Can be used to diagnose slow startup times.

       [1m--api-info  [22mDump API metadata serialized to msgpack and exit.

       [1m--embed     [22mUse standard input and standard output as a msgpack-rpc channel.  [1m:help --embed[0m

       [1m--headless  [22mDo not start a UI.  When supplied with [1m--embed [22mthis implies that the embedding application does not intend to (immediately) start a UI.  Also useful for ‚Äúscraping‚Äù
                   messages in a pipe.  [1m:help --headless[0m

       [1m--listen [4m[22maddress[0m
                   Start RPC server on this pipe or TCP socket.

       [1m-h[22m, [1m--help  [22mPrint usage information and exit.

       [1m-v[22m, [1m--version[0m
                   Print version information and exit.

[1mENVIRONMENT[0m
       NVIM_APPNAME
                   The name of sub-directories used within each XDG user directory.  Defaults to [1mnvim[22m.  [1m:help $NVIM_APPNAME[0m

       NVIM_LOG_FILE
                   Low-level log file, usually found at [4m~/.local/state/nvim/log[24m.  [1m:help $NVIM_LOG_FILE[0m

       VIM         Used to locate user files, such as init.vim.  System-dependent.  [1m:help $VIM[0m

       VIMRUNTIME  Used to locate runtime files (documentation, syntax highlighting, etc.).

       XDG_CONFIG_HOME
                   Path to the user-local configuration directory, see ‚ÄúFILES‚Äù.  Defaults to [4m~/.config[24m.  [1m:help xdg[0m

       XDG_STATE_HOME
                   Like XDG_CONFIG_HOME, but used to store data not generally edited by the user, namely swap, backup, and ShaDa files.  Defaults to [4m~/.local/state[24m.  [1m:help xdg[0m

       XDG_DATA_HOME
                   Like XDG_CONFIG_HOME, but used to store data not generally edited by the user, things like runtime files.  Defaults to [4m~/.local/share[24m.  [1m:help xdg[0m

       VIMINIT     Ex commands to be executed at startup.  [1m:help VIMINIT[0m

       SHELL       Used to initialize the 'shell' option, which decides the default shell used by features like [1m:terminal[22m, [1m:![22m, and [1msystem()[22m.

[1mFILES[0m
       [4m~/.config/nvim/init.lua[24m  User-local [1mnvim [22mLua configuration file.

       [4m~/.config/nvim[24m           User-local [1mnvim [22mconfiguration directory.  See also XDG_CONFIG_HOME.

       [4m$VIM/sysinit.vim[24m         System-global [1mnvim [22mconfiguration file.

       [4m$VIM[24m                     System-global [1mnvim [22mruntime directory.

